    <item>
      <title>Re: What clerics need</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=10573#M10573</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;What exactly is it that you think is "my solution"?&amp;nbsp; My main point on this thread is that I think all classes should be able to do "ok" damage with melee weapons, rather than the current state of "laughable" damage.&amp;nbsp; I think this would help clerics more than most other non-melee classes while still being something most classes would rally behind because it would be fun even if it didn't represent a significant&amp;nbsp;power boost for them, rather than argue endlessly about.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;In response to a random derail of the thread, I also suggested that there needs to be at least three classes able&amp;nbsp;to competently fill each group slot, NOT 2 as suggested.&amp;nbsp; Fewer than&amp;nbsp;three would cause the classes who can fill the slot to be grossly overdesired in groups, as clerics currently are.&amp;nbsp; I think druids and shamans are the logical choice for "primary healers" #2 and #3.&amp;nbsp; Brum (and you it seems) seem to feel that this would unbalance things in favor of shamans more so than they are currently unbalanced right now.&amp;nbsp; In reponse to that, I suggested that you pick another class as healer.&amp;nbsp; Since there's no way you can do that without overpowering someone (by your own definitions), you have two choices:&amp;nbsp; live with some amount of imbalance or create a new class.&amp;nbsp; The only way to meet ALL of the stated requirements and avoid overpowering (by your own definitions) existing classes would be to add a new one.&amp;nbsp; I personally think that's a stupid idea.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The best way to look at this entire situation is probably to think of it somewhat similar to the multiple slots for "dps".&amp;nbsp; If we consider typical groups to be comprised of 3 offense + 3 defense, where the 3 offense are usually "dps" and the 3 defense are "tanks", "slowers", and "healers", then we get to an interesting way of doing balance.&amp;nbsp; We can factor out the "tank" defensive slot and not worry about it, since most people feel it's reasonably well balanced as it currently is.&amp;nbsp; That leaves 2 defense slots shared by "healers" and "slowers".&amp;nbsp; For those two slots, we've got the following classes:&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;cleric, druid, shaman, enchanter, beastlord, bard.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Looked at at that granularity, from an overall game point of view, things are actually sort of in balance.&amp;nbsp; You need to choose 2 of 6&amp;nbsp;classes to fill 2 of 6 group roles.&amp;nbsp; It's only when you look a bit deeper and distinguish between dealing with damage by preventing it versus by healing it back (as most groups do when forming) that you&amp;nbsp;see a disparity.&amp;nbsp; If you could just grab 2 of the 6 defensive classes like you can grab 3 of the 9 dps classes for the 3 dps slots, things might work quite a bit better.&amp;nbsp; A few things get in the way of this.&amp;nbsp; First of all, slows don't stack at all, which means you simply cannot add two slowers and no healer and expect your group to function.&amp;nbsp; Secondly, healers don't have haste spells, so taking two healers and no slowers is kind of a pain in the butt also, since your melees would have to bring a large supply of haste potions to do proper dps.&amp;nbsp; You can't&amp;nbsp; work around not having a healer with healing potions and though it would be cumbersome to work around the lack of haste you could do it, but most groups don't ever consider doing so.&amp;nbsp; Therefore we end up with a situation where most people feel that they must have 1 healer + 1 slower.&amp;nbsp; But if the groups form up at random, you end up with many combinations which simply don't work.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;All of the combinations involving clerics work quite well, which is one reason why groups tend to grab them, as it gives them maximum flexibility to fill out that last slot.&amp;nbsp; Also, rez is totally covered.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;cleric + (shaman or enchanter or beastlord or bard) works quite well&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;cleric + druid works ok if you're willing to bring a bunch of haste potions for your melees.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;As things currently stand, the best combination with druid is almost certainly shaman, since the shaman brings a solid amount of extra healing power to make up for the healing gap between druids and clerics.&amp;nbsp; Beastlords are probably the next best choice for a druid, then enchanters.&amp;nbsp; Bard + druid is probably doable, but you're starting to push it when you have less than ideal healing and less than ideal slowing at the same time.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Shaman plus any of the other slowers is pretty much a total waste, with huge amounts of overlap.&amp;nbsp; Shaman healing is quite dramatically worse than clerics because they have slows, but in this case someone else is probably doing the slowing.&amp;nbsp; It might work if the shaman is really good and a bit overgeared, but otherwise the overlap makes all these combo pretty lame.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;All of the other combos simply don't work due to slows not stacking.&amp;nbsp; Thus 2 healers + 4 slowers to fill the 2 defensive slots doesn't work in many of its combinations.&amp;nbsp; I was trying to make a couple of the combinations work better while giving clerics a boost by suggesting that they get like a 40% haste spell.&amp;nbsp; It seems logical to me that this would be somewhat helpful and help multiple clerics stack in grouping situations.&amp;nbsp; Not sure why you dismissed it out of hand.&amp;nbsp; Seems like a good idea.&amp;nbsp; As a "haste class", I wouldn't have a problem with clerics getting a haste spell.&amp;nbsp; If shamans get a significant healing boost, this would be&amp;nbsp;a decent&amp;nbsp;way to help clerics out a bit, infringing on defensive group slots, rather than other group slots.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Then if they did something about making slows from the different classes stack a bit better, you could just grab 2 of the 6 defense classes for the 2 defense slots and get moving.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;If they don't do any of that, then they simply need to add a viable third healer and perhaps boost beastlord defensive capabilities a bit more so shamans would end up getting healing slots more often but at the same time get slowing slots less often.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;With a few tweaks (or with stances), druids would actually be ok if there weren't so many excess clerics floating around and filling up all the healer slots&amp;nbsp;caused by raid imbalances.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;But if you prefer to focus on crazy changes which infringe on tons of other classes and have no hope of actually happening, go for it.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by GlowingRune on &lt;span class=date_text&gt;11-29-2005&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=time_text&gt;05:53 PM&lt;/span&gt;</description>
